lf-published pulp fiction novellas, and song lyrics. Through these textual networks, Callaci shows how youth migrants and urban intellectuals in Dar es Salaam fashioned a collective ethos of postcolonial African citizenship. This spirit ushered in a revolution rooted in the city and its networks—an urban revolution that arose in spite of the nation-state's pro-rural ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCity and town lifexHistoryx20th centuryxTanzaniaxDar es Salaam. 0aCity and town lifexSocial aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxTanzaniaxDar es Salaam. 0aCity and town lifexSocial aspectszTanzaniazDar es Salaamy20th century. 0aCity and town lifezTanzaniazDar es SalaamxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntellectualsxHistoryx20th centuryxTanzaniaxDar es Salaam. 0aIntellectualszTanzaniazDar es SalaamxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrbanizationxHistoryx20th centuryxTanzaniaxDar es Salaam. 0aUrbanizationzTanzaniazDar es SalaamxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Africa / East.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311069634940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822372325423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822372325/original  a978-3-11-069634-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles